Presentation

One of the jewels of the Riviera, set in the heart of a superb forest domain

   Set between Cannes, Nice and Grasse, the Golf Club of Opio Valbonne is
   one of the jewels in the crown of the Riviera. Imagine an 18-hole
   course amidst the sea and the mountains, at the heart of a magnificent
   domain. Protected by 220 hectares of undulating landscape in the shade
   of century-old trees, where you will even find a Gallo Roman aqueduct !
   Just a few minutes from some of the most beautiful coastlines of the
   Côte d’Azur,  this site, sheltered from the wind, benefits from a sunny
   climate and an ideal geographical position.
   At the golf course, the Château de la Bégude**** offers you the
   opportunity to return to traditional values, which has contributed to
   the success of the region. The 17th century Bastide has been completely
   renovated and boasts a restaurant, overlooking the golf course, where
   the Chef offers an inspired Provence cuisine rich with colour and
   flavour.

Golf Course

   Opio Valbonne
   18holes | 5698meters | By72 | Architect : Donald Harradine (1966)
   In the heart of magnificent natural surroundings, between the mountains
   and the sea

   An exceptional location

   In the heart of the Côte d’Azur, the Opio Valbonne Golf Course has the
   advantage of an exceptional climate and ideal geographic surroundings,
   well-sheltered from the winds. It offers a unique scenery of sea and
   mountains, where the Alps interlace with the rivers of the
   Mediterranean.

   A magnificent Natural Park
   In a magnificent, undulating natural park of 220 hectares, the design
   of the course marries perfectly the rich vegetation and the different
   variety of trees. It is a course which has attracted the most demanding
   of European Golfers, who are always in search of originality and
   relaxation.

   A Course renovated in 2002
   The course, one of the oldest in the region, was designed in 1966 by
   the master of English architecture, Donald Harradine.
   Major work was undertaken in 2002, guided by the architect Robert
   Berthet.

   An absolute delight for the golfer
   A number of greens have been completely re-designed and significant
   modifications have been made to holes number 10, 11 and 14. The first
   nine holes require skillful mastering of the approaches and the irons.
   As for the last nine holes, they require long and regular drives.
   > Download scorecard

